019 so it\u2019s not a term used specifically for this type of character but it fits the game wonderfully. Your goal is to train as many strong and brave gladiators to fight in the final battle against another group. You have 1 year to accomplish this going from nothing to a well-established gladiator master.\n\n[u] Management? I just want to kill some bros[/u]\n\nNo one ever said that being a gladiator master didn\u2019t require any paperwork! You have to provide food and water for your gladiators and any other servants you have. You must build upgrades and hire employees to make everything run ever more smoothly and bribe powerful figures. This all sounds quite complicated but it\u2019s actually done really stylishly! The menu navigation is  easy and I never felt like I anything was hidden that was possible to do; although at first it took me a while to figure out that to hire new employees it was in the market menu however that could be a problem that lay with me not the game. \n\nAnother big plus is that equipment for your gladiators can be bought in the menu of a specific gladiator instead of in a long unclear menu where you\u2019re buying equipment and you can\u2019t remember who it was for or what it was called; I really liked that. Something I\u2019m not so fond of is that when you go to upgrade a weapon or a piece of gear both your options are highlighted in green if you can afford them or one in red if you cannot afford it. The thing I find most annoying is that the downgrading option which is getting a cheaper piece of equipment is always in green which has confused me at times when I was quickly changing armor. I would like to have it switched to a plain colour as it\u2019s always going to be available as you\u2019re only gaining money doing such an action.\n\n[u] I\u2019ll take my revenge! I mean, Claudius will [/u]\n\nAfter a couple of research options you can control your own gladiators, instead of them being A.I. controlled, to control their own lunges, dodges and blocks. This is actually done really well, you can see the skills you invested in earlier actually shown with increased combat ability as they\u2019re not 1% or 2% changes. Combat feels very fair; even if my gladiator has 100 less health I can still win if I keep dodging and striking him from behind. All your enemies are always balanced to your own level of gladiators .So if you invest all your money into one gladiator all opposing gladiators will also be that powerful thus it subconsciously forces you to even out your earnings. I think this approach is way better than a standard levelling curve as even if you were to cheat by adding extra money it would really make no difference to the actual skill you need to win duels. \n\n[u] Historical accuracy [/u]\n\nOf course this game relies heavily on history, in fact the sole reason that this game exists is probably because of the fact that this history exists. When it comes to historical accuracy of course you can only turn so much into a game before it becomes boring to play. A clear example of this is the fact that very often Roman gladiators didn\u2019t die at all, keep in mind that a gladiator is quite expensive and you don\u2019t want them dying all the time as the funding per fight wasn\u2019t that gigantic. However the developers of this game know that if no one would ever die then: what\u2019s the fun? So I don\u2019t blame them for keeping that out. \n\nBesides that a lot of things have been done right, a gladiator training center was really called a ludus and real historical gladiator classes have actually been recreated in game; although there is a thing I don\u2019t like about it which I\u2019ll get to later. I think the crowds and other characters have been recreated nicely wearing genuinely realistic Roman clothing and I can really only say good things about the historical accuracy which I think deserves some praise as often arcade style games only use it as inspiration. \n\nWhat I don\u2019t like is that all the different types of gladiators have been put into 3 very distinct classes. In real life the variations would\u2019ve varied more, even in the same class of gladiator. While I understand that it\u2019s quite a hassle to get everything in there, I do find it a downside and ties in with my point about a lack of customization at higher levels of gear. \n\n[u] Technicals [/u]\n\nPerformance wise I had no issue running this and neither should you, my older computer containing a GT620 was easily able to run this game as the total screen only contains about 200 pixels. (i5-7600K,1050TI 4GB OC, 8GB Ram, HDD 7200rpm) I did have an issue where I could not get it to run in fullscreen as it would move across to my secondary display. I found no way to change this back to the primary display, this might\u2019ve just been Windows 10, but having it just full-sized on my main display was fine playing as well since it\u2019s a 2D game. \n\n[u] Summary [/u]\n\nDomina, while not perfect is still incredibly fun and I\u2019ve had a blast playing it. Since playthroughs are short it\u2019s the kind of game you play when you don\u2019t know what to play. Even with its apparent lack of content I think it will keep its replayability, because even though reruns are the same per run it\u2019s still very fun even if it stays relatively the same. If the devs open up mod support at one point it will thrive harder than ever.\n\n[b] Score: 89/100 [/b]\n\nThis game was provided for free by the developers, however my opinion has not been influenced by it.\n\n[quote][url=https://store.steampowered.com/curator/23741321/]Follow our curator page,[b] Alexander's Club Curations[/b] if you like and want to see more reviews like this one.[/url][/quote]", "comment_count": 2, "received_for_free": false, "voted_up": true, "recommendationid": "48387837", "weighted_vote_score": "0.711869597434997559", "votes_up": 18, "steam_purchase": false, "timestamp_updated": 1547750103, "written_during_earl