 is a game that pretty much throws you into the pit (pun intended) and expects you to survive - or perish. Oldschool, like I said.\n\nOh, and you technically *can* control one of your gladiators yourself in a fight once you research 'mind control'.\nThat doesn't mean you *should*, however; gladiators with AI skill at 100 are so. much. better.\n\n\nWith that out of the way, DOMINA's main game mode, campaign, is a lot of fun. RNGesus can throw some funny, interesting or just mean events your way, which is fun and also fits with the overall oldschool feel of the game. And without wanting to spoil too much, there is an event at the very end of the game where the outcome is decided by your actions throughout the game. Gave me goosebumps all over when it happened, even though I had a general idea of what was going to happen. Overall, finishing the campaign took me a little less than 6 hours.\n\nAs for the (as of yet experimental) endless mode, I haven't tried that, but I asssume it'll give you a bit more freedom and opportunities in the long run, whereas the campaign limits your game to one year's time.\n\n\nIn any case, there are few things as gruesome, and outright bloody amazing as getting to throw a group of your most experienced and well-equipped gladiators at a bunch of fighters from another ludus. The word that comes to mind is 'meatgrinder'.\n\n\n[b]Verdict[/b]\n\nIn a gesture appropriate for a gladiator school management game set in ancient rome I give DOMINA a big THUMBS UP. If you're open to trying new things, enjoy lots and lots of blood and a soundtrack that gets said blood pumping, look no further than this game.", "comment_count": 0, "received_for_free": false, "voted_up": true, "recommendationid": "41150174", "weighted_vote_score": "0.522293031215667725", "votes_up": 1, "steam_purchase": false, "timestamp_updated": 1522407882, "written_during_early_access": false, "votes_funny": 0}, {"timestamp_created": 1522383956, "language": "english", "author": {"steam