ining is having your fighters fight among themselves, or by taking a gamble by sending them into the pit (it's less of a gamble once you memorized the dozens of pixel art equipment). Stats increases so ridiculously faster in battle that training is practically useless, something I found out halfway through the game.\nNumbering systems mean nothing to these devs, as gladiators level exponentially in battles, yet their stats are directly linked to said stats. Making it ridiculously easy to get a max level gladiator after level 40, ready to be sold, freed, or just because you feel like it, killed. Killing is a bad thing mkay. Except in the Colosseum.\n\nThe automatic AI is moderately fun to watch, although there's not much strategy or variety in it, and after watching it about 3 times it gets stale. The people with the highest stats win, practically always. There's no such thing as an underdog. If your guy is a lower level, he simply won't do damage to the other guy. Blood just splatters everywhere, but no damage!\nSo when you decide to control one of your gladiators yourself, you must make sure you remember to click which guy to play; which is great if there's 9 people participating because you can't select the 9th and strongest guy. And at random times it'll just not select someone automatically. Finally, the game never automatically selects the strongest warrior you have.\n\nWhen you get your random battle screen, the screen has this cutesy way of scrolling through all the possibilities, despite the host disposition already telling you who'ss hosting, the amount of fighters already being set, and the enemies being set, meaning the randomization animation is an absolutely and entirely useless gimmick.\n\nIt has this ridiculously annoying and meticulous card system where you drag cards into off-screen slots, as opposed to simply putting them on them through their stats screen.\nSpeaking of, scrolling through the stats screen makes zero sense. I still haven't been able