y first real reviews.)\n\nDomina is a game that puts you in the shoes of a wealthy heiress to a Gladiator Pit and learn the fundimentals of how one controlled their aggressive bunch of killers. you can train your gladiators in any category with the adjustments in their stats, as well as purchase new gladiators from either the Legate (essentially a roman general) and a the Magistrate (essentially a politician). Your goal is to win the final battle by the time the days end (unless you're on endless mode) and become the champion of Rome and obtain the hefty prize that would allow you to become one of the most powerful figures in Rome. You can essentially play in almost whatever terms you want (as long as you understand the mechanics of the gameplay). Do you have enough trust in your Gladiators level of A.I. to win the day? Or are you one who likes to take fate into your own hands and face the enemy head on? with the Mind Control perk you are capable of taking over your gladiator and keeping him alive to the best of your abilities. However I personally prefer to play without the Mind Control, for a leader could not control their soldiers every single movement, it was down to the soldier themselves.\n\nPros:\n-Graphics: I like the pixelated look personally, it adds it's own unique feel to the game, and I honestly don't know if the game would be the same Without this look.\n-Gameplay: It's a management game at it's finest, you can essentially control everything that happens from \"what type of people you hire?\" which leads to different benefits (Pro Tip: get the architect, they build permanant structures in your training field that increases the speed of your gladiators training, it's very good to get him early) to how your gladiators are training, what armor they are wearing, and even special perk cards you can add onto them and improve their skills and training speed.\n-Choices: Even tho this game focuses on the combat and training aspect, there are occasional moments where you are forced to choose between the Legate and the Megistrate on certain events. For example there could be a food shortage throughout the city and the MAgistrate is asking for X amount of Food, while the Legate is experiencing a drought in the border where his troops are patrolling, and he needs X amount of Water. You are in this situation forced to either help the legate and lose some water while making him happy, but upsetting the magistrate, helping the magistrate and losing some food while making them happy, but pissing off the legate, or you could choose neither and piss both of them off, but keep your resources. in the end each choice cna effect both the legates/magistrate's opinion on you (which means they may not pay for the expenses of one of your gladiators each) but can also effect the resources you need to stockpile.\n-Resource Management: The game is made in a way where it's incredibly easy to keep managing your resources, however you have to remember to keep buying each resource you need. Food and Water are essentials for keeping everyone fed and happy, while Wine is used to bribe the legate and magistrate to make them happy. However you cna get so preoccupied by managing your gladiators, making decisions and getting upgrades for your gladiators, that you can forget to get food and water sometimes. It doesn't help that they put the \"underground pit fights\" in the same place where you get food and water, so that can be a big distraction while you go into the menu just trying to get some resources you despreately need. All in all if you pay attention resources won't be an issue, just don't get distracted by your gladiators and your employees and you'll be fine.\n-Music: The music in this game is great. It is overpowering in situations like combat, and soft and gentle during decisions of choosing. It's the perfect mix of intense combative music and soft, calming music that helps you make good decisions in the game. Also if you pay attention you'll notice the music lines up with the game. I dare you to show me one countdown that doesn't line up with the hook to the song.\n-Dialogue: The Dialogue is unnerving and disturbing at times when it needs to be, and Hilarious at times when it needs to be. [spoiler](spoiler alert, there's allot of ball kicking from our female protagonist.)[/spoiler]\n\nCons:\n-A.I.: While I do like the idea of leaving the A.I to do it's thing, considering a leader never has full control over their soldiers. That doesn't change that the A.I. likes to do stupid things sometimes and lose to anoither gladiator who in all states was weaker then my dude, the only difference would be they had a higher A.I. scoring. So unless you plan on making it where you control your troops at all times, I recommend having your gladiators focus on A.I. training so they will have the best possible A.I. to pit up against the enemy. This does help with allot of victories. And while it is good that the A.I training shows results, that doesn't change that the A.I. can be just flat out silly sometimes and do stupid things and upset me.\n-Duration: if you Really played the game throughout the day, you could probably finish the overall champaign within about 1-2 hours, While I understand this is a management game and they can't go on as long as most other games without having a sense of repeatitiveness in it, that doesn't change that days can go by super fast (roughly every 5 seconds I think) and you only have a year to get ready, this doesn't leave allot of time to develop all of your troops, making it where you can't walk away or even Look away from the screen without pausing it if you expect to Win in the end. I will tell you now the difficulty of this game is pretty high, and the odds of you winning at the Very End are slim, I'm not gonna spoil anything about the ending, however that doesn't change that if you aren't prepared, you Will lose in the overall scheme of things. I still haven't technically won the game, but I have seen people on Youtube do it. So it's not impossible to win, it just takes all of your attention and timing skills to make your you use all the time at your disposal efficiently, which i'll be honest i'm not good at. So while this probably isn't an issue for hard-core management fans, if you are looking for some casual fun? this game is not for you, this game does have a difficulty factor to it, and only people who Truly understand the mechanics behind management games will get to the real ending on this game. That isn't to say the game isn't fun, it's just not for casual play (unless you're ok with watching your gladiators die to a sudden super buff enemy that will one hit them)\n\nTL;DR [spoiler](you ingrate)[/spoiler]: If you are a casual player this game isn't for you, winning requires all of your attention and thus casual play is not welcome here. If you are looking for a hard-core management game that requires most (if not) all of yo ur skills in a management game to win? get it right now, it's 66% on sale as I write this out.\n", "comment_count": 0, "received_for_free": false, "voted_up": true, "recommendationid": "38981173", "weighted_vote_score": 0, "votes_up": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "timestamp_updated": 1514914112, "written_during_early_access": false, "votes_funny": 0}, {"timestamp_created": 1514907106, "language": "english", "author": {"steamid": "76561197988341610", "playtime_forever": 616, "last_played": 1530313313, "num_reviews": 1, "num_games_owned": 129, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0}, "review": "I really liked this game, it does have small bugs etc. but also a good bit of entertainment. Absolutely worthwhile for the low pricetag.", "comment_count": 1, "received_for_free": false, "voted_up": true, "recommendationid": "38977205", "weighted_vote_score": 0, "votes_up": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "timestamp_updated": 1514907106, "written_during_early_access": false, "votes_funny": 1}, {"timestamp_created": 1514903242, "language": "eng