s with coin, wine, and private room or, ultimately, freedom. Their moral goes towards how well they will fight for you. You must also manage your relations with the Legate and Magistrate, as it them who organise the matches, and how much the like/dislike you will help determine the odds against you.\n\nThe plays as you would imagine it would if you were in charge of the Ludus. You don't participate in the fighting. You can research 'mind control' which allows you to control a single Gladiator in battle, but when you see how fast battles play out, you are best leaving it to the professional... The A.I. Your job is simply to manage the numbers. Food, Water, Money and Wine, all are required to run your Ludus, and it is up to you to make sure you have enough. You ultimately work your way towards the 'championship' at the year's end. Ensuring your Gladiators are in top form for the final tournament. Your choices and management will be tested here, more than ever.\n\nJust like in the movie and the series, the game will throw you a curveball at times, setting  up a match that is obviously meant for you to lose. Sometimes you have to make a choice of sending your champion and risking his life for the win, or sending in your newest recruit to certain death. It is here that i would have liked to seen a bit more depth to the Gladiators. Giving the underdogs at least a chance of winning against the odds, and becoming something of a legend. However, its all about the numbers. How much Health, how much Damage, how much Defense. \nIt's nice to see sometimes your Ludus champion (your best Gladiator - think Krixis) still wounded from the previous battle, and your up and coming Gladiator step in for this match (think Sparticus) and win. Gaining both skill and fame, he becomes stronger. The two then become a deathly duo.\n\nThe music. Oh lord, the music. If you watched the trailer and it kinda grabbed you, it only gets better. The fight setups to the fight start times with the music perfectly. So that when it says 'Go' the music is in its beefiest. It's a shame you can't slow the matches down, so that you may appreciate the animation, bloodshed and music more. There are some rounds that are won with a single blow. \n\nThere are a few things i would like to see put into the game, but all in all, if this is on Sale, you would be mad to miss it. It will more than triple the amount of hours you play it for than the dollars you pay for it.\n\n", "comment_count": 0, "received_for_free": false, "voted_up": true, "recommendationid": "38881996", "weighted_vote_score": "0.644341826438903809", "votes_up": 12, "steam_purchase": true, "timestamp_updated": 1514679358, "written_during_early_access": false, "votes_funny": 1}, {"timestamp_created": 1514673143, "language": "english", "author": {"steamid": "76561198036485584", "playtime_forever": 351, "last_played": 1515194088, "num_reviews": 27, "num_games_owned": 490, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0}, "review": "Very short and simplistic gladiator sim. Training is worthless, which is a disappointment, but fun for a sale price", "comment_count": 0, "received_for_free": false, "voted_up": true, "recommendationid": "38878947", "weighted_vote_score": "0.490943789482116699", "votes_up": 1, "steam_purchase": true, "timestamp_updated": 1514673143, "written_during_early_access": false, "votes_funny": 0}, {"timestamp_created": 1514667420, "language": "english", "author": {"steamid": "76561198043635794", "playtime_forever": 696, "last_played": 1514755511, "num_reviews": 20, "num_games_owned": 142, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0}, "review": "Graphically this game reminds me of the great Finnish game Assault Trooper (a late ninety-game). This mixes nicely with humoristic battle theme. On the other hand the game looks like quite blurry in some situations (for example the equipment view). \n\nThe actual gameplay is pretty simple but ruthless. Basically you are facing randomized but eventually improving gladiators and you need to c