ion, and I admire greatly the discipline of the devs - it's rare to see someone who understands the importance of coherence and is willing to drive everything around a central theme.  On the whole I appreciate it, but the devotion to theme does come with certain costs the devs presumably deemed acceptable.\n\nNotably, the gameplay isn't - at all - the careful, stolid management sim that some might have expected, since that would have run counter to the theme.  The gladiator management aspects exist to feed the sense of careless brutality, not to satisfy the sage planner.  If you were expecting to slowly build your house into a thriving and respected pillar of society, look elsewhere - this is a game about a determined woman clawing her way to the blood-soaked top.\n\nEven taking the gameplay as it is, though, strictly speaking it's somewhat flawed as a game.  Training is useful, but ultimately the power of your gladiators is based pretty much entirely on winning and performing well in the arena, which makes a good swathe of the management of your gladiators very secondary, other than buying gear.  The strategy of the game is fairly simplistic and it's not hard to figure out how to crack the game over your knee in the space of half a playthrough or so.  The option to personally command gladiators might serve, somewhat, at first, but from the midgame onwards battles are dominated by AI-controlled lightning-fast gladiators exploding their enemies in a shower of gore in a series of charges almost too quick to follow with the naked eye, let alone any kind of manual control.  Fair bits of the game are poorly explained, and the real-time nature of the game means there's constant pressure to keep trying to stay afloat instead of slowing down to learn more.  There's all kinds of minor niggles here and there of that nature that keep the gameplay from being particularly deep or engrossing.\n\nIn a sense, you might say that Domina is less of a game than it is an art piece.  But it is an art piece that is very good at what it does, and it still is very firmly a decent, fun, and playable game, albeit one dominated by its artistic message.  If you want to watch a society ripping itself apart for pleasure, pick up Domina and enjoy.  If you just want to watch pixel men explode into blood fountains to a pulse-pounding beat, have a blast.  Otherwise, caveat emptor.", "comment_count": 0, "received_for_free": false, "voted_up": true, "recommendationid": "38283429", "weighted_vote_score": "0.523355603218078613", "votes_up": 1, "steam_purchase": false, "timestamp_updated": 1513183002, "written_during_early_access": false, "votes_funny": 0}, {"timestamp_created": 1513130195, "language": "english", "author": {"steamid": "76561198076717216", "playtime_forever": 89, "last_played": 1513108481, "num_reviews": 16, "num_games_owned": 382, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0}, "review": "The game doesn't adequately explain what your goal is until you've been playing for about an hour, so your time up until then is just kind of wandering through the menus trying out things and then BAM you're in your first fight and you don't know why. You're going to be very confused very early when you can't control your character and you don't realize that 'mind control' is actually an upgrade you have to buy from an upgrade tree that isn't very intuitive to find early on.\n\nIt is fine to have a game that recognizes the skill of the AI, and you're intended to have your gladiators be AI lots of the time and that works, but it takes away from the player's desire to hack and slash into an arena. As a result this game is more of a 'gladiator arena simulator' than a gauntlet itself.\n\nThe gameplay is fairly solid, but it feels light on content. This game has good enough controls and combat is slightly simple, but still responsive and fun. The game could benefit a lot from a multiplayer mode where players could compete in arenas with others online, as well as a sandbox mode where you