 your gladiators when choosing them for a fight. Handling the jupiter cards (upgrades to gladiators) is especially wonky.\n\nHalf the professionals you can buy from the marketplace do nothing of use. The slots for assistants are limited and there's just about four that do anything half decent. Maybe the game is still in development and this will change but I can't see any reason to get a bard to block an assistant slot to raise morale when I can just toss a coin and a bottle of wine, both of which are an endless resource, at every gladiator to keep them happy. \n\nThere's a lot of gear to buy that all have distinct looks which is amazing, but the downside is 80% of the gear is priced so cheap that you'll just breeze through them to the best stuff. There's almost zero feeling of gradual progression when you have 4000 gp on you and the upgrades are somewhere in the ballpark of 5gp each.\n\nThen the worst part. The game actually has a difficult mechanic underneath but you're not told about it until the very end where you realize a mechanic earlier on that you felt was completely pointless suddenly becomes the deciding factor in whether you win or lose. There's no warning. You're just in an unwinnable situation if you didn't do a certain thing several times before. I won't spoil it but you'll see it on your first playthrough. It's super frustrating when you play a game you feel is super easy for 3 hours only to find out it was about something completely different in the end that you had no way of knowing because you weren't told. A really big blemish on an otherwise promising game.\n\nAll this said I'll still give it a recommendation. The theme is amazing, music is superb and the graphics are quite good. There's a lot of potential and if you can get this for a discount ( I paid 5 eur) the few hours you get now are worth it to support what it hopefully will become down the road.", "comment_count": 0, "received_for_free": false, "voted_up": true, "recommendationid": "3809