3 on 1 against. And if you take the reputation hit, you're more likely to get a crappy fight the next time, too.\n\nLevel scaling. So since you have a time limit, and the only way you can earn money is to win fights, you put your best fighter out there as often as you can. And because you win, the randomly generated opponents get stronger. This means that unless you use your best one or two fighters every time, you're going to get stomped. As long as your best fighter keeps winning, he'll get insanely strong and knock down 9 opponents in 2 seconds. But if that guy gets killed, then what? You've got a bunch of scrubs against AI that's been scaled to fight your best guy, and if you can't win, you can't earn money.\n\nReally lame random events. No, seriously. \n\n\"Your gladiator gets bitten by a snake. The gladiator dies.\"\n\n\"Your gladiator is suffering from sunstroke. What do you do?\n- Leave him out to practice in the blazing sun\n- Bring him inside to rest in the shade\"\n\nBring him inside to rest.\n\n\"You bring him inside to rest. He dies.\"\n\nThen you get random stuff that requires reflexes. If your fighter surrenders, you save him by clicking as fast as you can on the mouse and keyboard. The amount of time you have to click is random - sometimes you can't save him no matter how fast you click.\n\nIf you play it as an arcady game (you can play as your fighters):\n\nThe control scheme is really bad - no controller support and things move pretty fast.\n\nIf the dev had done away with the action stuff and focused on management depth, this game would be great. If he'd done the opposite, it probably would have been good too. But as is, the game doesn't do either strategy or action well and I don't see how it can be salvaged into a really memorable title. \n\nI've noticed the forums aren't too lively either, which usually means a game is close to being abandoned.\n\nLike I said, get it if it's $3-4. Don't pay more than that for it.", "comment_count": 15, "receive