ass every expectation i had for it and then some. When i had gladiators in the ring that i couldnt control (you can choose to control a gladiator later on.) i was on the edge of my seat, and since i was watching with a friend of mine I was actually cheering when my gladiators would succeed in the arena. This game is just so cool and i dont really know how to go about explaining it. To cut to the chase though you are Domina, the Lanista of the ludus left to you by your father. You can buy slaves who need to be trained to become good fighters, or buy for a much higher price a warrior that has already been in the ring. You have to manage your resources, like food, water, wine, and gold to make sure that you can keep the local politicians and your own gladiators happy. Your gladiators will go up against random challenges and you may or may not choose to control them. Regardless, the AI does a competent job of playing for you if you prefer to play that way, which is still very entertaining. I played on a slightly higher difficulty the first time around and man that was a challenge. I think the stock difficulty is a little bit too low, and i did find the game to run a painfully short. However there is an infinite-time mode. I recommend cranking the difficulty juuuuust up to \"normal\" for optimal fun/difficulty ratio. The stats on gladiators take a little while to figure out but after you have it, it's not hard to navigate. All in all it ia an excellent game and i am very glad it was gifted to me. It really is a decent representation of ludus management i imagine, with you having to navigate local politics as well as survive in the ring. This game is so amazing and unique and it does what it sets out to do unbelievalbly well, and that is be a fun and engaging ultra-violent pixel art Lanista experience. I thoroughly, THOROUGHLY, recommend. So. Much. Fun.\n\n\n\n(Update. Can confirm that endless mode is just the regular mode on loop. You get to keep your gladiators after th