nything in big fights impossible. Group fights are supposed to be chaotic, so I guess I can't complain.\nUI does its job in almost all cases, but fails in my opinion during the pre-fight menu: It is slightly cluttered, and sometimes annoying to look at.\n(14/20)\n\n\nGAMEPLAY AND CONTROLS:\nControls are intuative and fit the gameplay well. The gameplay itself... gets boring very fast. There is some variety in the fights, but you have to specificly gimp your game session if you want that variety (like lions) - otherwise its mostly the same old 1 dude versus 1 dude.\nThe game is challenging, but the constant randomness can be very irritating: It turns much of the game into a dice toss. Mainly, your far superior fighter can easily lose to enemy due to any reason at all, but most notably beause:\n1) Idiotic AI throwing a certain win, even when the AI value within the game is maxed.\n2) Enemy randomly having a Cursed Weapon buff, which you don't notice due to the UI. (Cursed Weapon is/was OP)\n\nThe game's difficulty curve is odd and inconvenient, and with the help of randomness it ruined much of the experience for me: Usually games are easy at the start, to get you going, and then ramp up the difficulty. DOMINA is difficult and frustrating at the start, then incredibly easy and boring at the midgame and end - making most of the game meaningless chore. Choosing a higher difficulty can help a little, but in my opinion the game is simply designed wrong in this aspect.\nI find it hard to decide whether to praise the game for not holding the player's hand, or chastice it for being a coin toss.\n(20/40)\n\n\nSOUND AND MUSIC:\nVoice acting and sound effects are tolerable. Music is surprisingly good, and sets the mood right.\n(17/20)\n\n\nOTHER FEATURES, BUGS AND GLITCHES\nGame has no multiplayer, but there seemed to be some options for Twitch: Streamers are propably thankful of that, but these options do not add any value for anybody else.\nGame seemed to work fine during the 