bout this game.  I'm going to recommend it based on the idea that if it appeals to you it's not expensive and can be a lot of fun if you're looking for something fairly simple to figure out but with the option to do some min-maxing.\n\nOn the one hand, while I really want to love it for its Rogue-Like qualities, gritty setting, and the combination of approachable simplicity combined with a certain kind of depth, it's just another game which punishes you for not tricking it - and once you figure out how to trick it a lot of the enjoyment of playing goes out the window - and I'm not really sure I want to keep grinding to see if there's a happy ending.  Expect to burn a couple hours on a playthrough to learn the mechanics as the 'tutorial' is just a roadblock to features and doesn't teach you anything.\n\n*SPOILERS* below.\n\nIf you win too much, the game starts stacking the 'deck' against you with fervor.  When you're given fights against impossible odds it turns out there's no penalty for throwing 1 naked guy hopelessly against them to die - and this actually works in your favor by adding a 'loss' to your stack and forcing the AI to throw easier guys at you next fight.  So by winning the fights that matter (the unavoidable fights which you have a count down toward and which pay your small fortunes) and throwing exhibition matches (get the same favor win or lose) with the free or 3-gold slaves you get, you can always have perfect standing with the two guys who won't ever go away and never help you no matter what you do for them or how good your standings are - even in the end when you win everything and are accused of murder, they don't help you and so you (the Domina) are swarmed by gladitors as an ending....  Neat.\n\nBy favoring a few guys and letting them steamroll really easy guys in exhibition and regular fights you can get their stats really high (any victorious fighters who don't die automatically get +2 to all stats, even if they never fought).  You also never need to train the ability to train the other two gladiator types as you can just buy already trained guys if you want those classes from the freeloading Legatus on the left or as prizes.  That's all after considering that you can take an unclasses slave into the arena, dodge around until a trident is dropped in the ring, then own just about anything that comes at you with a very little training.\n\nThe resource management and items of the game are a joke.  1 gold buys 30~50 of a given supply with no details.  You start out with way too much gold, it's too easy to buy helpers and upgrade, and you get way too much gold for winning fights, but it's 'balanced' by the super inflated and nonsensical costs of different equipment upgrades, right? - all 'upgrades' are always a def/atk upgrade, but the weight changes, meaning that you'll avoid certain upgrades until you can afford to move beyond them in one go.  When it dawns on you that you can sell the gladiators you get as prizes for winning fights (the cannon fodder with zero skills but hundreds of gold in equipment) you suddenly have more gold than you can spend.  If you ever just want to buy tons of food/water you can save+exit to menu, reload, buy a 10 stack of food 5 stack of water, rinse and repeat - apparently reloading the save game resets the market stack back to new game levels without having to wait for it to restock and removes the stock maximum.\n\nInstability.  For the most part, the game is pretty stable.  No hard crashes or anything like that.  I did have to save+exit and reload my save multiple times in a single run through (2.5 hours to do) because the game would get choppy, things would lag, and saving and reloading would fix it (this is how I discovered the Food+Water exploit above).  This seemed to happen more quickly when my garrison was full or near full with lots of guys doing the training actions.  There was also some lag during larger fights (the ones I'd throw 1 or 2 unclassed slaves into again