ew more things:\n\nDomina is a high-wire/nail-biter roguelike sim that sort of plays like the illegitimate child of Oregon Trail and Hotline Miami, if OT and HM broke into Sid Meier's house and conceived their forbidden lovechild in his garage while under the influence of LSD. \n\n(When I invoke Oregon Trail, I mean to conjure your most painful, rage-quit-inducing memories of Sally getting dysentery in Idaho and blowing away an hour or more of your \"perfect game\" progress like it was nothing. Similiarly, I suggest Hotline Miami because I want you to remember its masked, homicidal maniacs windmilling melee weapons and spilling gallons of pixel-y blood like they just huffed their weight in bath salts. The reason they're coupling in Sid Meier's garage without his knowledge is because, while there's some classical, society-building aesthetics in Domina, this definitely ain't your daddy's Civ-sim.)\n\nIt is not at all uncommon to get an hour into a new game of Domina, make a bad call about the potential risk associated with a given decision and basically wipe your game and have to start fresh, because there is literally no way you can come back from the loss within the time remaining. Moreover, when this happens, it will be in the blink of an eye: your stock will go from \"promising\" to \"junk\" in three to five glorious, horrifying, blood-drenched seconds.\n\nWhen this happens, it is awesome. Horrifying and gut-wrenching, obviously, but also totally, totally awesome. I have literally broken a sweat playing this game, due to the sheer terror of moments like these.\n\nAnd I have done this again and again, because (see above), this game is great.\n\nEverybody should play this game.\n\n\nPS: I liked Domina more before it had a save feature--no save, hardcore/OG Rogue style made the horrifying lows that much more intense--but I understand that, as an independent developer, when RPS specifically calls you out for a feature, you kind of have make something happen there. Sav