you ownership. With a new home and title of Ludista and Domina, you plan to participate while citizens are still interested in bloodshed. As local games are scheduled, you see an opportunity to participate during this interest of bloodshed. Hopefully that old woman is wrong and they will let you win.\n\nAs you and your gladiators progress and become more experienced, more will come in. The Doctore will show up to help you train your gladiators with upgrades, ranging from controlled breathing to throwing weapons. Next the Magistrate and Legate will barge in to provide their own services. The old Magistrate offering slaves and the Legate offering gladiators for sale; both having a satisfaction meter that can fluctuate with the different actions you take regarding them. Further in, 2 tables will appear, one for the Regional Championship games (4 needed to qualify) and the other for Jupiter's Blessings cards to attach to gladiators for boosts. Various random interactions will litter the playthough that can pit you against choosing between the Magistrate or Legate (or no one) or bring add how the outside world is.\n\nThe gameplay revolves around training and fighting gladiators, starting with 2 gladiators and a slave. Providing 3 classes they can be, 1 default and 2 locked behind upgrades, with their own weapons and armor style. Once you click them, it will bring various stats and tools used to balance out their training. Showing how their temperment/morale is due to various effects that will affect how they act, how much weight they have, a tool to balance training between various aspects such as agility or how smart the AI will play (Meditate), a character picture to upgrade or degrade armor, give them rewards, and kill, grand freedom, or sell them. \n\nWhile the Doctore is the main employee you will use, 9 others are available to fill up the 3 other spots. As the Architect has the only permanent upgrades, but will usually be employed the rest of the year, you must choose which one is best. With all bringing in their own speciality, one will make healing faster while the other may steal armor or spy to get secrets. \n\nRight by your 365 day deadline is how many days till a local battle, spreading out more towards the end of the year. You can organize pit fights (There is a bug where you can turn invisible though) and exhibition matches to gain favor between these times. Each will greet you with a screen showing information for who's hosting it (and their satisfaction with you), so you can pick your gladiator and choose to use AI or control it yourself with the Mind Control upgrade, reward and cost, the type, and your opponents. This can range from being against 1 gladiator to 2 gladiators and a lion. I do not know if your standing with the host effects anything, but my gladiator was only chained if it was bad. Be warned for backing out though, as the host will be upset with you even if your gladiators need more training.\n\nUpon acceptance, you will come into the arena with your opponents, all conditions will be done before it starts with the crowd cheering. If you have a high Meditate level your gladiator will fight with more confidence and easily handle the opponent, especially in a group; contrasting with a low level staying behind and not picking up on the opponent's cues. As your opponent will have the same things you have, don't think they will always be ill prepared. Winning will grant you buffs and rewards while losing will grant nothing or a consolation reward that can depend if the crowd was pleased with the amount of bloodshed. If you surrender, you will play a minigame to determine if the gladiator is killed, but it can be a really hard minigame as you can't click fast enough. The only way is clicking everything you can click. \n\nWhile I have avoided talking about the soundtrack, I do have to mention it here. It works well in showing that this is the world of gladiator fights. This is most prominent during the fights and certainly brings in the mood. During training it is calm but still brings in that you will have to fight sooner or later. Heads up though, it can be a little too loud when first opening up to the title screen.\n\nDomina has short to long runs depending on what you do and if you purposely throw the game away. With the replayability possibility high, everything is randomized including names, events, and stats of slaves/gladiators. So the game will call everyone by their title rather than their randomized name with the exception of the gladiators and slaves. \n\nAs most of the story is behind the tutorial, it allow the player to deal with pieces at a time when going past a certain action. Choosing not to go with the tutorial will give you everything immediently. While it can be possible to beat it in the tutorial mode, choosing not to will greatly increase your chances. I do recommend going over it at least once though so you can learn everything without having to rush it or be confused.\n\nWith the main drawing point is Domina being set in the Roman Empire when gladiators were popular, I did research some things int he game. It was interesting to see what could of influenced certain aspects of the game and showed it did take history into account.\n\n[h1]Overall[/h1]\n+ Brings in history\n+ The crowd in the arena\n+ The bloodshed of course!\n+ Random events, which can be hilarious\n+ Tutorial not meant to beat, but to give you piece by piece advice and story\n+ If you are a streamer, there is Twitch integration\n\n- No saving system. I do get why it is not implemented and runs do run short enough unless you live long enough to last for an hour or two. However, in a game like this it is important to have a saving feature of some kind as most people will not be able to stay on the computer for a long time. It could of easily worked in a way that Enter the Gungeon does it now where you can save and quit and once you go back in it is automatically deleted. Or an autosave feature where it saves after each battle. I know that this will turn people off till the developer decides to implement it. (Saving system has been added)\n- Invisible gladiators during pit fights. Remember to switch to AI if you have Mind Control once this is fixed!\n\nDomina is one of those games you need to learn how to play before you can appreciate it for what it is. It is a simple trainer down to it's core as you try to keep your gladiators shaped up compared to your opponents and happy but with a Roman twist. I was actually so attached to a specific gladiator that I couldn't bare to see them go. Which makes it harder to let them go if they request freedom. If you love strategy games, especially ones like these, I recommend picking this up. You would be surprised at what the ending brings. \n\nThough be sure you know there is no saving feature, and while this will not affect me recommending this game, it may affect whether or not you will buy it.\n\n[code]  [url=http://saveorquit.com/2017/04/07/review-domina/] Read the full review here![/url] [/code]", "comment_count": 0, "received_for_free": false, "voted_up": true, "recommendationid": "30923885", "weighted_vote_score": "0.561913728713989258", "votes_up": 10, "steam_purchase": false, "timestamp_updated": 1494403331, "written_during_early_access": false, "votes_funny": 0}, {"timestamp_created": 1491227714, "language": "english", "author": {"steamid": "76561198007254277", "playtime_forever": 944, "last_played": 1521467745, "num_reviews": 28, "num_games_owned": 353, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0}, "review": "Easily one of the better indie games to come to steam.  The developer put a lot of love and passion into this creation.  I first heard of it through Youtuber's who had gotten Beta Access.  This had to be one of the quickest purchases that I've ever made that I didn't regret shortly afterwards.  It could use a save function but hey, at the time of writing this, it's v1.0. \n\nDomina is a Rogue-Like Spectac